1 Introduction

1.1 Background

This document was written for the dual purposes of summarizing the work done on the alternative recognition vs mimicry project and acting as my second rotation report within the biochemistry department. All the code was written by me unless explicitly noted but this project was started by Andre Fonseca who wrote the early exploratory code, consolidated the dataset, and contacts, performed the modeling using a modified internal pipeline which is helped create. All the scripts and functions which are mentioned will be in the format script_name.R or function_name.

The idea for the project grew out of a desire to be able to quantitatively describe the difference between alternative recognition and molecular mimicry, spurred by earlier work which seemed to point towards well known cross-reactive examples not neatly fitting into current working definitions for TCR cross-reactivity. Andre originally conceived this project as a short communications paper but after bringing me onto the project for some months he shifted direction to focus on a larger, data driven version of the project.

1.2 Our data source: The VDJ/XREAC Dataset

The dataset was made from the VDJ database. It is built around the idea of a T-cluster. A T-cluster consists of a single T-cell and all of it’s known epitopes. To be a known cross-reactive T-cluster, it must, by definition, contain at least two epitopes. This dataset is ideal since it gives us a large collection of different T-clusters and known cross-reactive epitopes.

Initially had all the the analysis in a single document but as the complexity grew I rewrote much of it to be cleaner and terser within their own functions. The functional scripts are named with the prefix find_ while testing new features the scripts with testing_ was used.


This code was taken from find_pairwise_blosum.R which, along with the other code used to generate these plots (and this report) can be found on our GitHub.
This report is interactive and contains all the code needed to run all the analysis is embedded in the Rotation_Report 2_2.qmd version of this document. The one notable exception is the final section in this report which makes use of get_contacts packet to predict the intermolecular interactions between each T-clusters’ TCR and each of the different epitopes.

For the purposes of this report I will focus on T-cluster 7218. This particular cluster was chosen because of the relatively large size of the the T-cluster that particular T-cell was expect to bind, which was among the largest with a total of 10 cross-reactive peptide epitopes.

2 Heatmaps for BLOSUM and RMSDs

2.1 Pairwise BLOSUM scoring peptides

Image by LabXchange © The President and Fellows of Harvard College

BLOSUM is a kind of scoring function developed to distinguish the similarity or difference of an amino acid substitutions. As a tool developed with genetics in mind, summarizes the frequency at which we observe a substitution for one amino acid to another. This is a statistical measure, which makes use of the log-odds score for every combination of amino acid substitutions forming a matrix. For example, the substitution of alanine to glycine (score = 0) would be less dramatic than alanine to tryptophan (score = -3). The advantage of this is we can infer biological similarity of amino acids, in general. The disadvantage of this is that because this is based upon high level and sequence based information it is most relevant for comparing two closely related proteins where we are likely able to assume that the same sequence accomplishes a similar role biologically as with aligning two evolutionary divergent alleles to each other. What this does not fully capture is the context-specific similarities and and differences resulting from the surrounding topological and physicochemical factors stemming from a particular molecular context. We could make our BLOSUM score more specific to a particular context by regenerating the scores using only sequences from our particular context, assuming that enough sequences to make such comparisons meaningful but this requires a large dataset of examples to draw upon.

To score each cluster with BLOSUM, I created a script find_pairwise_rmsd.R which extends the functionality of the rmsd() function from the bio3d package to allow pairwise comparisons of the backbones of a set of structures, given the desired chain or chains and the directory of .pdb files. The visualizations for comparing different peptides to one another has primarily been with heatmaps, I experimented with hierarchical clustering of the rows and columns but found the ease of comparison between multiple heatmaps more useful than the peptide grouping provided from directly clustering the heatmaps.

In purple you can see how each peptide compares to each other peptide inside of T-cluster 7218. The higher the score, the more similar the peptides. Scores are based on the cumulative scores scores from comparing each peptide to each other on an amino acid basis.

2.2 What is the role of RMSD?

RMSD is a measure of the root mean square of points in space. In this context we can compare the distances of the alpha carbons to one another. Higher scores correspond to a greater average distance between the the alpha carbons of each each amino acid position. There are trade-offs here of course too, which atoms you choose to compare position can make a difference. Implicit to choosing to compare the RMSD of the alpha carbons, we are focusing on the backbone alone, ignoring the side chains entirely. If we want to compare the RMSD of two structures with the same sequence, as with the same TCR binding to two different peptide epitopes, we can calculate RMSD based off all atoms in every amino acid, including, notably, the side chains of each amino acid.

2.3 Pairwise RMSD of the TCR

Unlike with the BLOSUM scoring of the peptide, this comparison is a measure of the TCR, not the peptide directly. The pairwise RMSD comparison of each TCR confirmation is shown in green and still uses the epitope target as a label. Lower RMSD is indicative of a more related peptide.

2.4 Pairwise RMSD of the CDR Regions

Following initial analysis of the RMSD of the TCRs, we wanted to focus in on the possible differences at the CDR level which could provide a clearer picture of differences that a TCR might undergo to accommodate binding to different epitopes. In order to accomplish this, we faced the challenge of finding and implementing a method for subsetting the TCR. In the end this came down to defining the CDR regions in such a way it would work for all TCR clusters.

Most of the interactions expected in TCRpMHC binding are thought to come from the complementary determining regions (CDRs), especially CDR3. As the TCR makes contacts with different peptides we might expect that we would see the most change in shape at the CDR regions. By exclusively focusing on these regions, we might also ignore less related noise from smaller shifts of the TCR overall. Finding these regions requires knowledge of TCR structure and nomenclature. Small, highly variable CDR regions are sandwiched between invariant framework regions. There can be differences in the number of amino acids in the variable region, especially in the CDR3 region so disambiguating FR from CDR regions can be non-trivial. Thankfully there are conventions for labeling and indexing amino acids in the TCR, most notably the IMGT nomenclature for framework (FR) and CDR regions.

  • cdr1 from 27 to 38

  • cdr2 from 56 to 65

  • cdr3 from 105 to 117

This could provide more context for the role of the side-chains in recognition but potentially less about how the TCR itself has to flex to fit different peptides

3 Dendrogram Comparisons

3.1 Hierarchical clustering of peptides based on TCR CDR RMSDs

We can make use of hierarchical clustering to arrange related peptide or peptide induced differences on the TCR. By arranging the peptides (or the TCRs which recognize them) according their relatedness (i.e. RMSD, BLOSUM score, or edit distance) we can for groups of relatedness which could indicate mimicry within a group and alternative recognition outside of the group.

First if we look how a basic dendrogram would separate the peptides based off their biochemical properties.

3.2 Hierarchical clustering peptides based of biochemical properties

3.3 Tanglegrams

Another plot which allows to direct comparisons on how different metrics are grouped based off RMSD, BLOSUM, or edit distance, is a tanglegram. It is simply two hierarchical trees that that are matched to each other with arrows to highlight how a peptide is being grouped. There are measures to compare the how related the groupings or taxonomy from one method is to another. This relatedness between how the leaves are arranged on the trees between two trees is known as entanglement. I used the dendextend package for the added functionality and control of the plots as well as for calculating entanglement.

Entanglement 0.532

3.5 How much does it matter if we use the whole structure for RMSD vs just the CDR3?

RMSD can only be calculated beween the atoms which are shared by both structures. When comparing peptides RMSD for example, we must calculate the RMSD with respect to the backbone, most commonly the the Ca alpha carbon. I wrote and implementation extending the rmsd() from bio3d package which first only calculated RMSD for the alpha carbons but later came made this selection optional; this allowed for the all atoms to be included from each residue which is could be preferred when comparing structures with identical sequences, as with the shared TCR inside each T-cluster. Interestingly, RMSD signatures were different when i compared the CDR regions either looking at all atoms or just the alpha carbons.

3.6 Comparing using all atoms vs just the backbone of the CDR3

4 Levenshtein Similarity

Levenshtein Distance (or it’s inverse Levenshtein Simularity) is a metric for measuring the number of transformations (deletions, insertions or substitutions), collectively known as the edit distance to transform one string to another. For comparing amino acids, the more amino that are different between the two peptides and the more different the two peptides are in length, the larger the edit distance will be. To aid in performing this function i created a script find_pairwise_distances which compares each peptide to each other peptide and generates the scores for each combination. To calculate similarity, I made use of an implementation from the RecordLinkage package by Sariyar and Borg.

5 Seq Logos of T-Cluster:

To visualize the similarities and differences of peptides inside of a T-clusters another way, we can use sequence logos. Sequence logos can be used to show the relative frequency or here, probability having a particular amino acid at a given position. The advantage of this approach is we can can see highly conserved amino acid positions. Highly conserved amino acids between within groups of a single cluster might indicate groups of epitopes which are recognized through similar interactions by the same TCR (molecular mimicry).

5.1 Seq Logo Plot

6 Energy interactions / GetContacts

Previously our lab made a series of figures making use of the package GetContacts to summarize the interactions between the CDR and the peptide. The different type of interactions are visible on the key. Those starting with “hb” are different types of hydrogen bonds. These contact makes can be made either from static structures or from molecular dynamic simulations.

7 Conclusions and Future Directions

Here I have outline some of the methods our lab has used to elucidate the differences between alternative-recognition and molecular-mimicry cross-reactivity. These methods can form the basis of future analysis. Current work in our lab and with our collaborator will focus on a data driven approach and could include additional work generating molecular dynamic simulations with further analysis of the contacts and the energy of the complexes. Our group has also considered including non-machine learning based classifications.
